# pr

> Paginate or columnate files for printing
> More information: https://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/pr

- Print multiple files with a default header and footer:

`pr {string value: file1} {string value: file2} {string value: file3}`

- Print with a custom centered header:

`pr -h "{string value: header}" {string value: file1} {string value: file2} {string value: file3}`

- Print with numbered lines and a custom date format:

`pr -n -D "{string value: format}" {string value: file1} {string value: file2} {string value: file3}`

- Print all files together, one in each column, without a header or footer:

`pr -m -T {string value: file1} {string value: file2} {string value: file3}`

- Print, beginning at page 2 up to page 5, with a given page length (including header and footer):

`pr +{int value: 2}:{int value: 5} -l {string value: page_length} {string value: file1} {string value: file2} {string value: file3}`

- Print with an offset for each line and a truncating custom page width:

`pr -o {string value: offset} -W {string value: width} {string value: file1} {string value: file2} {string value: file3}`
